  brain_region: 'Insula',
  brain_region_hi: 'इंसुला',
    core_science: 'Interoception is the brain\'s ability to sense and interpret the internal physiological state of the body, such as heart rate, respiration, hunger, and muscle tension. This process is managed by the insular cortex, which acts as a bridge between bodily states and conscious feelings. Your brain uses these interoceptive signals to construct emotions; for instance, a racing heart and shallow breathing might be interpreted as fear or excitement. Individuals with high interoceptive awareness are highly skilled at identifying these physical sensations early. This skill allows them to regulate their emotions effectively, as they can address physiological changes before they escalate into full-blown emotional distress. Conversely, poor interoception is linked to emotional dysregulation, as individuals struggle to connect their mental stress with their physical symptoms.',
    in_your_life: 'We often feel anxious or irritable without understanding why, ignoring the physical signals our body is sending us. This disconnect makes emotional regulation difficult. By developing your interoceptive awareness, you can learn to read your body\'s signals, using physical clues to understand and manage your emotional states before they overwhelm you. Understanding this neural wiring helps you build sustainable habits that work.',
    practice: 'Close your eyes for one minute and focus entirely on feeling your heartbeat without taking your pulse, practicing your interoceptive awareness. This immediate application signals to your brain that this information is highly valuable, driving the process of long-term memory consolidation.',
    closing_wonder: 'Is your mind creating your feelings, or is it just translating the whispers of your body?'
