  brain_region_hi: 'प्रीमोटर कॉर्टेक्स',
    core_science: 'Empathy is not just a social concept; it is deeply rooted in our biology through mirror neurons, located in the premotor cortex and inferior parietal lobe. Mirror neurons fire both when you perform an action and when you observe someone else performing that same action. This neural mirroring allows you to simulate the movements, intentions, and emotions of others in your own brain. When you see someone smile, your mirror neurons activate the same pathways that govern smiling, helping you understand their state of mind. This system forms the biological foundation for empathy and social bonding, allowing us to connect with others on a visceral level. However, this mirroring means we easily absorb the emotional stress of those around us, highlighting the need to maintain healthy emotional boundaries.',
    in_your_life: 'We are highly sensitive to the energy and moods of the people we spend time with, often absorbing their stress without realizing it. This neural mirroring can drain our energy. To maintain your emotional balance, you must be conscious of your environment, protecting your space while remaining empathetic to others. By incorporating this biological insight into your workflow, you protect your focus.',
    practice: 'Today, when interacting with someone who is stressed, consciously remind yourself that their stress is theirs, protecting your own emotional state from mirroring theirs. By taking this active step, you break the cycle of passive consumption and initiate structural plasticity in your sensory networks.',
