  brain_region_hi: 'स्वायत्त तंत्रिका प्रणाली',
    core_science: 'Heart Rate Variability, or HRV, is the measure of the variation in time between each heartbeat. Managed by the autonomic nervous system, HRV is a key indicator of cardiovascular health and emotional resilience. A high HRV indicates a flexible autonomic system that can transition smoothly between the sympathetic (fight-or-flight) and parasympathetic (rest-and-digest) states. When you are stressed or anxious, your HRV drops, indicating a rigid, stressed system that is stuck in fight-or-flight mode. Over time, low HRV is linked to chronic fatigue, emotional burnout, and poor health. You can actively improve your HRV through regular aerobic exercise, deep breathing, and quality sleep, training your autonomic system to remain flexible and resilient in the face of daily pressures. This regulatory control is critical for maintaining cognitive focus and cardiorespiratory health over long stressful periods.',
    in_your_life: 'We think of stress as an emotional state, but it is physically reflected in the rigid rhythms of our hearts. If you want to build resilience, you must train your heart to be flexible. By prioritizing physical health and deep relaxation, you can improve your HRV, helping your body recover from stress quickly and maintain emotional balance. Try incorporating this method today.',
    practice: 'Engage in ten minutes of slow, rhythmic breathing today, aiming for six breaths per minute to help balance your autonomic nervous system. This brief practice forces your brain to build new networks, reinforcing positive habits at a physical cellular level over time.',
