  brain_region_hi: 'वेन्ट्रोमेडियल प्रीफ्रंटल कॉर्टेक्स',
    core_science: 'Fear Conditioning occurs when the brain associates a neutral stimulus with a stressful event, a process managed by the amygdala. For example, if you experience a car accident, your brain might associate the sound of screeching tires with fear. Fear Extinction, on the other hand, is the process of weakening this association by repeatedly exposing the brain to the stimulus in a safe environment. This extinction process is managed by the ventromedial prefrontal cortex, which learns to inhibit the amygdala\'s response. Extinction does not erase the original fear memory; instead, it creates a new, safe memory that competes with the old one. To succeed, fear extinction requires repeated, safe exposure, helping the prefrontal cortex strengthen its inhibitory pathways and helping you reclaim control over automatic emotional reactions.',
    in_your_life: 'We often avoid situations that trigger our anxieties, unaware that avoidance actually strengthens the fear memory in our brains. To overcome your fears, you must expose yourself to them in safe, controlled steps. This exposure allows your brain to learn that the threat is no longer present, building new pathways of confidence. By incorporating this biological insight into your workflow, you protect your focus.',
