  brain_region_hi: 'पीयूष ग्रंथि',
    core_science: 'Endorphins are neurotransmitters produced by the pituitary gland and hypothalamus in response to pain, stress, or intense physical exertion. The word endorphin translates to endogenous morphine, reflecting their ability to bind to opioid receptors in the brain and block the transmission of pain signals. Beyond pain relief, endorphins stimulate the release of dopamine in the reward centers, creating a feeling of euphoria and ease, often referred to as the runner\'s high. This chemical response is an evolutionary adaptation designed to help the body push through physical challenges. In daily life, you can stimulate endorphin release through intense exercise, laughter, and even eating spicy foods, utilizing the body\'s natural chemistry to relieve stress, elevate mood, and restore physical and mental well-being.',
    in_your_life: 'When we feel mentally stressed or physically tense, we often turn to passive distractions that do not address the physiological tension. To relieve this stress, you should engage your body\'s natural pain relief system. Incorporating intense movement or shared laughter into your day can trigger a release of endorphins, bringing immediate mental and physical relief. This is essential for cognitive growth.',
