  brain_region: 'Orbitofrontal Cortex',
  brain_region_hi: 'ऑर्बिटोफ्रंटल कॉर्टेक्स',
    core_science: 'The Somatic Marker Hypothesis, proposed by neuroscientist Antonio Damasio, suggests that decision-making is a process influenced by bodily sensations, or somatic markers. When you face a choice, your brain retrieves past emotional experiences associated with similar options, triggering physical responses like heart rate changes or muscle tension. These physical sensations are processed in the orbitofrontal cortex and ventromedial prefrontal cortex, acting as intuitive markers that guide your decisions. Instead of relying purely on logic, which takes significant time and energy, your brain uses these bodily signals to filter options quickly. This research shows that emotions and physical sensations are not distractions to rational thought, but are essential guides, helping you make complex decisions by providing intuitive clues about potential outcomes.',
    in_your_life: 'We are taught to ignore our gut feelings and make decisions using logic alone, believing emotions lead to errors. In reality, your body holds a physical library of past experiences. To make better decisions, you must learn to listen to these physical sensations, using your body\'s intuition to guide your choices. Understanding this neural wiring helps you build sustainable habits that work.',
