  brain_region_hi: 'लिम्बिक सिस्टम',
    core_science: 'Positive Resonance is a term coined by psychologist Barbara Fredrickson to describe the brief, micro-moments of shared positive emotion and connection between people. At the neural level, this resonance is characterized by synchronized brain activity in the limbic systems of both individuals, along with matching heart rates and mutual releases of oxytocin. These moments are not limited to close relationships; they can occur with a stranger, a barista, or a colleague. Research shows that experiencing regular micro-connections stimulates the parasympathetic nervous system, improves vagal tone, and reduces systemic inflammation. These benefits build physical and emotional resilience over time. Positive resonance highlights that human connection is a physical event that nourishes our nervous system, showing that our well-being is deeply connected to the micro-moments of connection we share.',
    in_your_life: 'We often view casual interactions with strangers or colleagues as unimportant, rushing through our day in isolation. In reality, these brief moments of shared warmth are small biological nutrients for your nervous system. To support your mental health, try to connect with others during these daily opportunities, sharing a smile or a kind word. By incorporating this biological insight into your workflow, you protect your focus.',
