  brain_region: 'Prefrontal Cortex',
  brain_region_hi: 'प्रीफ्रंटल कॉर्टेक्स',
    core_science: 'Creativity requires the balance of two distinct cognitive processes: divergent thinking and convergent thinking, both managed by the prefrontal cortex. Divergent thinking is the ability to generate a wide variety of unique ideas, exploring multiple possibilities without judgment. This process relies on a relaxed, flexible executive network that allows unusual connections. Convergent thinking, on the other hand, is the analytical process of evaluating, refining, and selecting the best idea from your options. This process requires focused, logical attention. A common creative mistake is attempting to use both modes simultaneously: criticizing your ideas while generating them. This conflict blocks the creative flow. To work efficiently, you must separate these phases, dedicating blocks of time to brainstorming without judgment, followed by separate sessions for evaluation.',
    in_your_life: 'We often criticize our ideas the moment they appear, killing our creative drive before it can begin. This critical approach is a conflict of cognitive modes. To improve your creativity, separate the generation of ideas from their evaluation, allowing yourself to brainstorm freely before you begin the process of refining and selecting. Recognizing these biological constraints allows you to design your day for efficiency.',
    practice: 'Spend ten minutes writing down as many ideas as possible for a project, banning all self-criticism during this brainstorming session. This brief practice forces your brain to build new networks, reinforcing positive habits at a physical cellular level over time.',
