    fact_title: 'Synesthesia',
    fact_title_hi: 'सेंसेशन का मिश्रण',
  brain_region: 'Association Areas',
  brain_region_hi: 'संवेदी जुड़ाव क्षेत्र',
    core_science: 'Synesthesia is a neurological condition where stimulation of one sensory pathway leads to automatic, involuntary experiences in a second sensory pathway. For example, hearing a sound might trigger the visualization of a color, or tasting a food might trigger a physical sensation. This phenomenon is caused by increased cross-talk and connectivity between the sensory association areas of the brain. While full synesthesia is rare, we all utilize sensory metaphors, such as describing a color as loud or a voice as sweet. This cross-sensory mapping is a powerful tool for creativity. By training your brain to connect different sensory inputs, you can build rich, associative neural networks, helping you generate unique ideas and express concepts in ways that resonate deeply with others.',
    in_your_life: 'We tend to think in isolated categories, separating sights, sounds, and ideas. This separation limits our creative expression. To expand your creativity, try to connect different senses in your work. Describe an abstract idea in terms of a physical texture, or design a project while thinking about its visual rhythm. By incorporating this biological insight into your workflow, you protect your focus.',
    practice: 'Take a project you are working on and describe its core concept using only sensory words: its color, texture, sound, and temperature. By taking this active step, you break the cycle of passive consumption and initiate structural plasticity in your sensory networks.',
    closing_wonder: 'What if the boundaries between your senses are not walls, but bridges waiting to be crossed?'
