    core_science: 'Cognitive Flexibility is the brain\'s ability to transition between different concepts, adapt to unexpected changes, and find multiple solutions to a single problem. This skill is managed by the anterior cingulate cortex and prefrontal networks, which monitor conflict and adjust behavioral strategies. When a strategy fails, a flexible brain quickly suppresses the old approach and activates new rules. Conversely, cognitive rigidity leads to repetitive, unsuccessful behaviors, a common response to stress. A flexible mind is essential for creativity, as it allows you to view problems from multiple perspectives and adapt to new information. You can train this flexibility by challenging your routines and exposing yourself to diverse viewpoints, strengthening the neural networks that support adaptation and cognitive health. This ensures cognitive efficiency.',
    in_your_life: 'When plans change unexpectedly, we often react with frustration and cling to our original ideas, which increases our stress. This rigidity blocks our ability to find solutions. To improve your resilience, practice embracing change as a creative challenge, using the disruption to train your brain to adapt and find new paths forward. By aligning your daily routines with these biological rhythms, you can succeed.',
    practice: 'If a minor plan changes today, pause and list three alternative ways to handle the situation, training your cognitive flexibility. This simple exercise converts passive knowledge into a physical shift, helping you build lasting focus and resilience in your daily routines.',
