    fact_title: 'Latent Inhibition',
    fact_title_hi: 'अव्यक्त निषेध',
  brain_region: 'Thalamus',
  brain_region_hi: 'थैलेमस',
    core_science: 'Latent Inhibition is the brain\'s automatic filter that classifies familiar stimuli as irrelevant, preventing them from reaching conscious awareness. Managed by the thalamus and dopamine pathways, this mechanism protects the prefrontal cortex from sensory overload. For instance, you do not constantly notice the pattern of your wallpaper or the sound of the clock. However, research shows that creative individuals often have low latent inhibition. Their brain\'s filter is slightly open, allowing familiar details to reach conscious awareness. This access to raw sensory data allows them to notice subtle connections and details that others ignore. While low latent inhibition requires high cognitive control to prevent distraction, it is a primary driver of creative insight, providing the mind with the raw material needed to see the world in a new way.',
    in_your_life: 'We often walk through the world on autopilot, ignoring the familiar details of our environment. This automatic filtering limits our creative inputs. To fuel your creativity, you must learn to override this filter. Actively paying attention to the familiar sights and sounds around you can help you discover new inspirations in everyday things. Recognizing these biological constraints allows you to design your day for efficiency.',
