    core_science: 'The Aha Moment, or sudden insight, is a distinct cognitive event where a solution to a problem appears in conscious awareness. EEG and fMRI studies reveal that immediately before an insight, there is a sudden burst of high-frequency gamma-band activity in the right superior temporal gyrus. This brain region is responsible for processing metaphorical language and connecting distant concepts. This gamma burst is preceded by a brief increase in alpha-band waves, which represents a sensory blink - a moment where the brain shuts out external distractions to focus internally. This research shows that insights are not random; they are the result of the brain\'s internal search, requiring a moment of quiet focus to allow the subconscious solution to break through into consciousness.',
    in_your_life: 'We often chase insights through intense, focused effort, which can block the brain\'s internal search. To experience more breakthroughs, you must allow your brain to blink. Stepping away from your work and creating moments of quiet, internal focus can help the subconscious solutions rise to your conscious awareness, bringing that sudden moment of clarity. By incorporating this biological insight into your workflow, you protect your focus.',
