  brain_region_hi: 'फ्रंटल लोब',
    core_science: 'Cognitive Disinhibition is the temporary weakening of the frontal lobe\'s executive filters, which normally suppress unusual thoughts, feelings, and sensory details. While these filters are essential for daily functioning and logical thinking, they can restrict creative expression by blocking unconventional connections. When these filters are relaxed, either through fatigue, meditation, or specific states of mind, cognitive disinhibition occurs. This state allows unusual and diverse information to enter conscious awareness, providing the raw material for creative insights. Research shows that many highly creative individuals have a natural capacity for disinhibition, allowing them to see connections that others filter out. Learning to regulate this filter - relaxing it to generate ideas and strengthening it to refine them - is a key skill for creative work.',
    in_your_life: 'We often struggle to think outside the box because our executive mind is constantly filtering out unusual thoughts. To boost your creativity, you must learn to relax these internal filters. Creating safe spaces where you can brainstorm without logical rules or self-criticism can help you access unique ideas that your mind would normally suppress. Recognizing these biological constraints allows you to design your day for efficiency.',
