    core_science: 'Playfulness and exploration are not just childhood activities; they are powerful stimulators of adult neurogenesis and brain plasticity. When you engage in play, exploration, or try new things, your brain releases neurotrophic factors like BDNF, which supports the survival and growth of new neurons in the hippocampus. Playful activity also reduces stress hormones like cortisol, which are known to suppress neurogenesis. This combination of high BDNF and low cortisol creates an optimal environment for neural growth and learning. In adults, maintaining a playful, curious attitude toward challenges encourages the brain to build new connections, preventing cognitive decline and boosting creative problem-solving. This research demonstrates that play is a biological necessity for maintaining a flexible, youthful, and highly creative brain throughout your life.',
    in_your_life: 'We tend to view play as a luxury or a waste of time once we reach adulthood, focusing entirely on productivity. This serious approach can lead to rigid thinking. To support your brain\'s health, you must incorporate curiosity and play into your routine. Approaching challenges with a playful mindset can help you find creative solutions while promoting brain health. This is critical for daily focus.',
