  brain_region_hi: 'फ्रंटोपोलर कॉर्टेक्स',
    core_science: 'Analogical Reasoning is the cognitive process of transferring information or meaning from a particular subject to another. This ability is managed by the frontopolar cortex, the most anterior part of the prefrontal cortex, which is highly developed in humans. When you solve a problem by drawing an analogy from an unrelated field (for example, comparing computer networking to highway traffic), your frontopolar cortex integrates these distinct mental representations. This cross-domain mapping is a primary source of creative innovation, allowing you to apply successful solutions from one area to another. By exposing yourself to diverse disciplines, you build a rich library of mental models, helping your frontopolar cortex make these creative leaps and find novel solutions to complex, real-world challenges. This biological cross-talk is the ultimate foundation of creative thinking.',
    in_your_life: 'When facing a difficult challenge, we often look for solutions within our own field, limiting our options. To find innovative answers, you should look outside your industry. Drawing analogies from nature, art, or other fields can help you see your problem in a new light, sparking unique and effective solutions. Understanding this neural wiring helps you build sustainable habits that work.',
