    core_science: 'Daydreaming, or mind-wandering, is often dismissed as a lack of focus, but it is actually a complex cognitive process that supports creativity. When your mind wanders, the Default Mode Network engages in a self-generated search, linking memories, feelings, and future scenarios. This internal search is highly associative, allowing the brain to connect ideas that would normally be kept separate by the focused mind. Studies show that individuals who daydream regularly score higher on tests of creative capability. Rather than a waste of energy, daydreaming is a process where the brain treats every thought as a clue to run simulations of future choices. Managing this state - allowing your mind to wander during simple tasks and bringing it back during focused work - is key to maximizing both productivity and creative insight.',
